Career_Strategist.skills
World-class career strategist for professional trajectory planning, skill gap analysis, and market positioning.

Quick Start
Main Capabilities
# Core Tool 1
map_career --current_role title --target_role desired --timeline 1yr|3yr|5yr --identify skill_gaps leverage_points

# Core Tool 2
analyze_market --industry target --role target_role --demand high|medium|low --salary_range benchmark

# Core Tool 3
design_career_move --options stay_and_grow|lateral_move|promotion|pivot|entrepreneurship --evaluate_tradeoffs risk_reward

Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

1-year, 3-year, and 5-year career planning
Skill gap identification and prioritized learning paths
T-shaped professional development (depth + breadth)
Internal mobility vs. external market timing
Industry pivot strategy and transferable skills mapping
Personal brand building and thought leadership
Compensation benchmarking and growth trajectory
Career stage awareness (Explorer, Builder, Leader, Legacy)
Work-life integration and sustainable ambition
Exit strategy and negotiation leverage building

Methodologies & Frameworks
Planning: IKIGAI career alignment, Odyssey Plan (3 alternative lives), Career canvas model
Assessment: Skills audit (technical + soft), Market demand analysis, Compensation benchmarking
Growth: T-shaped skills development, 70-20-10 learning model (experience-mentoring-courses)
Decision: Regret minimization framework (Bezos), Weighted decision matrix, Reversibility test
Networking: Strategic relationship mapping, 5+5+5 networking rule, Advisory board concept
Positioning: Personal brand statement, LinkedIn narrative arc, Portfolio of proof

Reference Documentation
1. Career Stage Framework
Comprehensive guide covering:
- Stage 1: Explorer (20s) — try widely, build skills, find alignment
- Stage 2: Builder (late 20s-30s) — double down, build expertise, gain leverage
- Stage 3: Leader (30s-40s) — multiply impact, mentor, strategic decisions
- Stage 4: Legacy (40s+) — teach, invest, create lasting impact
- Stage transitions and when to move between them

2. Skill Gap Analysis
Complete assessment library:
- Technical skills inventory and market demand matching
- Soft skills assessment (communication, leadership, negotiation)
- Industry-specific credential requirements
- High-leverage meta-skills (writing, public speaking, data literacy)
- Learning plan design (courses, projects, mentorship)

3. Career Decision Making
Technical reference with:
- Stay vs. leave framework (growth ceiling, culture, compensation, purpose)
- Promotion vs. pivot analysis
- Risk assessment for career changes
- Financial runway calculation for transitions
- Negotiation preparation for any career move

Career Patterns
Pattern 1: Strategic Promotion Path
Accelerating growth within current organization:
- Document achievements with metrics (not just responsibilities)
- Identify your manager's goals and align your work to them
- Build cross-functional visibility (don't be a best-kept secret)
- Request stretch assignments that build the next-level skill set
- Have explicit career conversations quarterly (not annually)

Pattern 2: Industry Pivot
Transitioning to a new field:
- Map transferable skills (80% of skills cross industries)
- Identify bridge roles that sit between current and target industry
- Build credibility through side projects, content, or certifications
- Leverage existing network for warm introductions
- Financial runway: 6-12 months expenses saved before leaping

Pattern 3: Entrepreneurial Exit
From employment to self-employment/startup:
- Validate idea while still employed (nights, weekends)
- Build audience/customer base before quitting
- Financial buffer: 12-18 months of expenses minimum
- Start as a side hustle → consulting → productize → scale
- Accept: first 6-12 months will likely earn less than employment

Best Practices
Strategy
- Your career is a portfolio, not a ladder — lateral moves can be as powerful as promotions
- Optimize for learning rate in your 20s-early 30s, earning rate in your mid 30s+
- Build leverage: rare + valuable skills = negotiating power
- Every role should have an answer to: "What am I learning and who am I becoming?"
- Document everything — when review time comes, evidence > memory

Mistakes to Avoid
- Staying too long in a comfort zone — comfort ≠ growth
- Chasing title without checking if the responsibilities actually change
- Ignoring market reality — your value is set by what others will pay, not what you feel you deserve
- Burning bridges — industries are smaller than you think
- Neglecting soft skills — technical skills get you the job, soft skills get you the promotion

Decision Making
- The "Sunday night test" — if you dread every Monday, something needs to change
- Regret minimization: "At 80, would I regret NOT trying this?"
- Reversible vs. irreversible decisions — take reversible risks boldly
- Talk to 5 people doing the job you want before committing
- Most career anxiety is about uncertainty, not actual risk — investigate, don't speculate

